I kind of don=E2=80=99t understand   the trade here?

A highly anticipated decision by the US Securities and Exchange Commission =
on whether to approve a spot-Bitcoin exchange-traded fund quickly morphed i=
nto a major cybersecurity incident on Tuesday.
The SEC=E2=80=99s X account was compromised and a fake post claiming that t=
he agency had green lit plans for the products fueled a brief surge in the =
price of the world=E2=80=99s biggest cryptocurrency. It also has sparked an=
 investigation by US authorities into how a social media account at Wall St=
reet=E2=80=99s main regulator was compromised. =E2=80=A6
The breach gave fodder to crypto faithful who have long viewed the commissi=
on=E2=80=99s chair,=C2=A0Gary Gensler, as an enemy due to his zeal to rein =
in the industry. The irony of a cybersecurity incident befalling a regulato=
r that=E2=80=99s repeatedly warned of crypto=E2=80=99s online vulnerabiliti=
es was not lost on critics who have spent years waiting for the SEC to appr=
ove a Bitcoin ETF. Traders have been speculating for weeks that the agency =
could approve several of the products as soon as Wednesday.
In statements late Tuesday, the regulator said that it would work with law =
enforcement to investigate the incident, the unauthorized access had been t=
erminated, and that the post wasn=E2=80=99t made by the SEC or its staff. I=
n a separate statement, Gensler clarified that no decision on ETFs had been=
 made.

Look, I have no inside information, but most of the reporting I have read a=
bout spot Bitcoin ETFs has said that=C2=A0
=09the SEC is going to approve them,=09by the end of=C2=A0today, and=09this=
 is public knowledge that everyone=C2=A0believes.

So you would think it would be pretty priced in? It just does not seem to m=
e like there would be a ton of alpha in (1) constantly refreshing the SEC=
=E2=80=99s Twitter account, (2) looking for a tweet saying =E2=80=9Cokay sp=
ot Bitcoin ETFs are cool now,=E2=80=9D and (3) buying Bitcoin on the news. =
Which implies there would not=C2=A0be a ton of alpha in (1) buying a bunch =
of Bitcoin,=C2=A0(2) hacking the SEC=E2=80=99s Twitter account, (3)=C2=A0tw=
eeting =E2=80=9Cokay spot Bitcoin ETFs are cool now=E2=80=9D and (4) sellin=
g your Bitcoin into the resulting enthusiasm.
There was a little though:
The false post on the SEC=E2=80=99s X account was up for a number of minute=
s before the agency clarified that it was inaccurate. In that period, Bitco=
in posted a relatively modest jump to almost $48,000 from about $46,700 bef=
ore falling back toward $45,000.
Eh? If you bought Bitcoin at=C2=A0$48,000 upon seeing that tweet, and then =
sold it at $45,000 after realizing that the tweet was fake, I would love to=
 hear from you. Why? Why not just wait? If you think=C2=A0Bitcoin is worth =
$48,000 when the SEC approves spot Bitcoin ETFs, then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0the tweet was fake, but if the contents of the tweet turn o=
ut to be true=C2=A0today, won=E2=80=99t you regret selling yesterday?
  [1]

Fine, yes, probably=C2=A0someone hacked the SEC=E2=80=99s Twitter=C2=A0to d=
o some market manipulation here: They wanted to bet on, what, a 2.5% short-=
term move in Bitcoin prices, and they made that bet pay off=C2=A0with a fak=
e SEC tweet. But I have   suggested before that there are two possible reas=
ons to issue fake announcements that move asset prices:
=09Market manipulation: You buy the asset, you issue the fake announcement,=
 the price moves, you sell it at a profit; or=09General trolling and hijink=
s: You don=E2=80=99t buy the asset, you issue the fake announcement, the pr=
ice moves, you have a laugh and high-five your online friends.

Doesn=E2=80=99t it seem at least=C2=A0possible=C2=A0that this hack was just=
 trolling? It didn=E2=80=99t move Bitcoin prices that much, and it shouldn=
=E2=80=99t have:=C2=A0The fake announcement was something that everyone exp=
ects to actually be true today. But it is very funny? The key element of on=
line trolling is irony, and there is plenty of irony here. Like:=C2=A0
=09The crypto community and the SEC do not particularly like each other: Ge=
nsler=E2=80=99s SEC has launched a   broad and   aggressive crackdown on cr=
ypto, and it is only going to (probably!) approve spot Bitcoin ETFs today b=
ecause   a court forced it to. If you=E2=80=99re a Bitcoin enthusiast with =
the skills to hack the SEC=E2=80=99s Twitter, you might want to manipulate =
the price of Bitcoin, but you might also just want to make the SEC look bad=
.=09Having the SEC (1) announce that Bitcoin ETFS are approved, (2) walk ba=
ck that announcement, and then (3) announce it again, for real this time, t=
he next day, really is quite embarrassing. Like if the hacker made the SEC =
say something outlandish and false, that would be a little funny. But makin=
g the SEC say something true a day early=C2=A0is extremely funny.=09In addi=
tion to cracking down on crypto, one of the SEC=E2=80=99s big regulatory pr=
iorities under Gensler has been  punishing companies=C2=A0for  cybersecurit=
y incidents.
  [2]
=C2=A0The SEC once   sued a company for using weak passwords, and its enfor=
cement director said that the case =E2=80=9Cunderscores our message to issu=
ers: implement strong controls calibrated to your risk environments.=E2=80=
=9D But apparently the SEC=E2=80=99s Twitter was compromised because it  di=
dn=E2=80=99t turn on two-factor authentication. Nyah nyah nyah nyah nyah!

I don=E2=80=99t know, the whole thing works better as trolling than as mark=
et manipulation.=C2=A0
A few further ironies. First, it does bear mentioning that X, formerly Twit=
ter, is owned by Elon Musk, who (1)   loves trolling and (2) hates the SEC.=
 =E2=80=9CI want to be clear. I do not respect the SEC. I do not respect th=
em,=E2=80=9D is one of the nicer things Musk has   said in public about the=
 SEC. It is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0convenient and funny =E2=80=A6=C2=A0that Musk=E2=
=80=99s Twitter was used yesterday to make the SEC look stupid. I mean, it=
=E2=80=99s not necessarily great for Twitter/X/Musk   as a business matter:

The high-profile breach comes at a time when X and billionaire owner Elon M=
usk are seeking to win back trust from both users and advertisers, many of =
which have been dismayed by Musk=E2=80=99s free-for-all style of leadership=
 since his 2022 takeover. Musk has pivoted away from some of the prior regi=
me=E2=80=99s efforts to rein in offensive or harmful content, and has sever=
ely scaled back staff to save on costs. Those cuts have led to regular bugs=
 and outages.
=E2=80=9CThis has to be the most sophisticated use of a stolen Twitter acco=
unt ever,=E2=80=9D said Alex Stamos, chief trust officer at SentinelOne and=
 former security chief at Meta Platforms Inc. =E2=80=9CAt a minimum, this i=
ndicates that the hollowed-out X team can=E2=80=99t keep up with advances i=
n account takeover techniques.=E2=80=9D

But it=E2=80=99s definitely a point for Musk in his long dumb game of troll=
ing the SEC.
To be clear, I am not saying it is=C2=A0likely=C2=A0that Elon Musk, who con=
trols Twitter, took over the SEC=E2=80=99s account in order to tweet a fake=
 announcement to troll the SEC. I think the likelihood of that is close to =
zero. I am just saying that it would be the absolute funniest Money Stuff s=
tory of all time. Just all of my interests, right there.
Another irony: I like to say around here that =E2=80=9Ceverything is securi=
ties fraud,=E2=80=9D and so of course when this story came out people email=
ed me to say =E2=80=9Cis this securities fraud yuk yuk yuk.=E2=80=9D But: n=
o? I mean, nothing here is legal advice, and everything is securities fraud=
, but let=E2=80=99s say that someone hacked the SEC to manipulate the price=
 of Bitcoin. Bitcoin is not a security? The SEC   thinks that almost every =
crypto asset is a security, but it really does make a single explicit excep=
tion for Bitcoin.
  [3]
 So if the SEC figures out who hacked its Twitter account, and if it figure=
s out that that person did it to make a quick profit on Bitcoin by manipula=
ting the market and deceiving investors, that=E2=80=99s still not securitie=
s fraud. It=E2=80=99s regular fraud, it=E2=80=99s wire fraud, maybe it=E2=
=80=99s commodities fraud, but whatever it is is not under the SEC=E2=80=99=
s jurisdiction. The SEC =E2=80=9Csaid that it would work with law enforceme=
nt to investigate the incident,=E2=80=9D but it has no power=C2=A0itself=C2=
=A0to bring charges against anyone for manipulating Bitcoin.
Still, there are securities that are tied to the price of Bitcoin, and whos=
e prices would be influenced by news about Bitcoin ETFs, and which were arg=
uably manipulated by this fake tweet. The most obvious examples would be =
=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 spot Bitcoin ETFs? Those don=E2=80=99t trade yet. Because t=
he SEC hasn=E2=80=99t approved them. So the fake tweet couldn=E2=80=99t hav=
e manipulated them. But Bitcoin=C2=A0futures=C2=A0ETFs=C2=A0do=C2=A0trade, =
as does the Grayscale Bitcoin Trust (GBTC), a pot of Bitcoins that hopes to=
 convert into an ETF. I suppose you could have manipulated their prices wit=
h this tweet. The tweet went out after 4 p.m. so the stock market was close=
d, but the price of the ProShares Bitcoin Strategy ETF did in fact bounce a=
round a bit in after-hours trading yesterday; it closed at $22.72 and spike=
d as high as $23.50 at 4:12 p.m., after the tweet. So, sure, securities fra=
ud, fine.
Anyway, the great counter-troll here would be for the SEC to  announce toda=
y =E2=80=9Cyou know what, all the Bitcoin ETF applications are rejected, we=
=E2=80=99ll see you in court again. We were=C2=A0going to approve them, but=
 it turns out that the Bitcoin market is still too vulnerable to manipulati=
on, as you can tell by the fact that someone hacked our Twitter to manipula=
te Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D

