   =20
      Elsewhere in Bitcoin ETFs
   =20
 =20

One rude but not entirely inaccurate way to describe the business model of =
Grayscale Investments LLC is:
=09Grayscale operates a pot, the Grayscale Bitcoin Trust (GBTC), into which=
 people can put Bitcoins.=09They cannot take them out.=09Grayscale pays its=
elf 2% of the value of the pot every year in fees.

This is not a good business model, when you describe it that way =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0who would put Bitcoins into the pot? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is an extr=
emely=C2=A0good business model if you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0describe it t=
hat way. There=E2=80=99s like  $29 billion in the pot. The fees are good. M=
eanwhile people whose Bitcoins are in the pot sometimes  sue to get them ou=
t, or at least to cut the fees, but that doesn=E2=80=99t work.
This description is very rude because Grayscale does=C2=A0want=C2=A0people =
to be able to get their Bitcoins out: It has  filed to convert GBTC into an=
 exchange-traded fund, which would allow for efficient creations (putting m=
ore Bitcoins in) and redemptions (taking Bitcoins out). And Grayscale sued=
=C2=A0SEC to force it to allow this conversion, and  last year it won, and =
everyone expects the SEC to approve Grayscale=E2=80=99s application to turn=
 GBTC into an ETF  by today. And a bunch of other issuers have filed to lau=
nch Bitcoin ETFs, and the SEC will probably approve them too, and GBTC will=
 have competition.
We  talked a bit on Monday=C2=A0about how this will affect Grayscale=E2=80=
=99s business model. One problem is: The ETF structure will allow investors=
 to take Bitcoins out of GBTC. Another problem is: All those=C2=A0other=C2=
=A0Bitcoin ETFs will charge=C2=A0much lower fees=C2=A0than Grayscale. Grays=
cale has already said that its fees will go down to 1.5% once it converts i=
nto an ETF, which is less than the current 2%, but still way more than the =
0.3% that BlackRock plans to charge. I wrote:

If you are the first person to offer =E2=80=9CBitcoins in a pot=E2=80=9D as=
 a product, you can charge a huge premium.
But eventually, like, BlackRock will catch up, and then you probably can=E2=
=80=99t.

A reader emailed to point out that this isn=E2=80=99t necessarily the whole=
 story. If you are the first person to offer =E2=80=9CBitcoins in a pot,=E2=
=80=9D people will put Bitcoins in your pot, and GBTC does have $29 billion=
 of Bitcoins. And those Bitcoins have appreciated=C2=A0in value: Most of th=
em were put in the pot at considerably lower Bitcoin prices than today=E2=
=80=99s $46,000-ish, and Grayscale  stopped putting new Bitcoins in the pot=
  in 2021. If you bought GBTC shares in 2019, or most of 2022 or 2023 for t=
hat matter, your shares are worth much more than you paid for them.
This is good for you, generally, but it is a tax problem: If you=C2=A0sell=
=C2=A0your GBTC shares, you=E2=80=99ll have a big gain and have to pay taxe=
s on it. If you just keep those shares, you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes (yet). =
That is a reason not to sell.
Soon, probably, you will have your choice of Bitcoin ETFs. They will all be=
 about the same, and you might prefer to buy one with 0.2% fees rather than=
 one with 1.5% fees. But if you=C2=A0already own=C2=A0shares in Grayscale=
=E2=80=99s Bitcoin trust when it converts to an ETF, the math isn=E2=80=99t=
 so simple. If you=C2=A0sell=C2=A0the Grayscale ETF and=C2=A0buy=C2=A0a che=
ap one, you will save on annual fees =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you=E2=80=99ll prob=
ably pay a lot of taxes on your gains.
  [4]
=C2=A0Paying 15% or 20% capital gains taxes on 50% or 80% gains on your GBT=
C shares might look a lot more expensive than paying an extra 1.3% per year=
 in fees.=C2=A0

