      Alternative data
   =20
 =20

I don=E2=80=99t know, here=E2=80=99s a paper finding that when bankers in N=
ew York are visiting the Federal Reserve Bank of New York a lot, that is ba=
d for the=C2=A0stock market:
We introduce taxi ridership between the Federal Reserve (Fed) Bank of New Y=
ork and large financial institutions headquartered in New York City as a no=
vel proxy for Fed=E2=80=93bank face-to-face interactions. We document a neg=
ative relation between past Fed=E2=80=93bank interactions and future stock =
market returns, particularly on days around the Fed=E2=80=99s public announ=
cements. We also find significantly elevated Fed=E2=80=93bank interactions =
immediately following the lifting of the Federal Open Market Committee blac=
kout. Our findings suggest that the Fed increases its information gathering=
 via face-to-face interactions when it possesses negative private informati=
on about the condition of the economy.
The paper is =E2=80=9CWhen Bankers Go to Hail: Insights into Fed=E2=80=93Ba=
nk Interactions from Taxi Data,=E2=80=9D by Daniel Bradley, David Andrew Fi=
ner, Matthew Gustafson and Jared Williams, and I guess that makes sense: Wh=
en the Fed is more worried about the economy, it meets with bankers more of=
ten, and measuring those meetings gives you some signal about the economy.
The problem is that=C2=A0taxi rides=C2=A0are a weaker measure of those meet=
ings than they used to be.=C2=A0From  the paper:
We generally employ a daily sample that runs from January, 2009, through De=
cember, 2014, where each day is defined as 5:00am through 4:59am the follow=
ing day. The year 2014 saw a large increase in the use of rideshare apps by=
 businesses and the first public release of the taxi data under New York St=
ate=E2=80=99s Freedom of Information Law (Rao 2015, Saitto 2014, White 2015=
, Whong 2014). Significant patterns in rides may reflect the movements of s=
mall sets of individuals, and substitution by any of them away from taxis d=
ue to changes in business practice or due to concerns about privacy could r=
esult in a significant loss of signal.
If you wanted to measure bank/Fed meetings in 2024, you=E2=80=99d use =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Uber data? (Or has everyone permanently gone virtual, and you=
=E2=80=99d use Zoom data?) I hope Uber Technologies Inc. is selling that da=
ta to some hedge funds.

