dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  the trade here</a>?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A highly anticipated decision by the US Securi=
ties and Exchange Commission on whether to approve a spot-Bitcoin exchange-=
traded fund quickly morphed into a major cybersecurity incident on Tuesday.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s X account was compromised an=
d a fake post claiming that the agency had green lit plans for the products=
 fueled a brief surge in the price of the world=E2=80=99s biggest cryptocur=
rency. It also has sparked an investigation by US authorities into how a so=
cial media account at Wall Street=E2=80=99s main regulator was compromised.=
 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The breach gave fodder to crypto faithful who =
have long viewed the commission=E2=80=99s chair,=C2=A0Gary Gensler, as an e=
nemy due to his zeal to rein in the industry. The irony of a cybersecurity =
incident befalling a regulator that=E2=80=99s repeatedly warned of crypto=
=E2=80=99s online vulnerabilities was not lost on critics who have spent ye=
ars waiting for the SEC to approve a Bitcoin ETF. Traders have been specula=
ting for weeks that the agency could approve several of the products as soo=
n as Wednesday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In statements late Tuesday, the regulator said=
 that it would work with law enforcement to investigate the incident, the u=
nauthorized access had been terminated, and that the post wasn=E2=80=99t ma=
de by the SEC or its staff. In a separate statement, Gensler clarified that=
 no decision on ETFs had been made.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, I have no inside information, but most o=
f the reporting I have read about spot Bitcoin ETFs has said that=C2=A0</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">the SEC is going to approve them,</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">by the end of=C2=A0today, and</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">this is public knowledge that everyone=C2=
=A0believes.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you would think it would be pretty priced i=
n? It just does not seem to me like there would be a ton of alpha in (1) co=
nstantly refreshing the SEC=E2=80=99s Twitter account, (2) looking for a tw=
eet saying =E2=80=9Cokay spot Bitcoin ETFs are cool now,=E2=80=9D and (3) b=
uying Bitcoin on the news. Which implies there would not=C2=A0be a ton of a=
lpha in (1) buying a bunch of Bitcoin,=C2=A0(2)<em> hacking</em> the SEC=E2=
=80=99s Twitter account, (3)=C2=A0<em>tweeting </em>=E2=80=9Cokay spot Bitc=
oin ETFs are cool now=E2=80=9D and (4) selling your Bitcoin into the result=
ing enthusiasm.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/33957045.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMDkvYml0Y29pbi1mbHVjdHVhdGVzLWFmdGVyLWRlYnVua2VkLXBvc3QtY2x=
