07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7c8a9f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  you have some duty to keep secret<=
/a>. If you work for Boeing Co. and you put the bolts in wrong and trade on=
 that information, that=E2=80=99s bad: You learned the nonpublic=C2=A0infor=
mation in your job, and you had a duty to Boeing to use it only for the goo=
d of Boeing rather than trading on it. If you=E2=80=99re the <em>pilot</em>=
, don=E2=80=99t buy puts when the door flies off. (Land the plane!) But if =
you are just a regular person and you go to McDonald=E2=80=99s and buy a bu=
rger and say =E2=80=9Cthis burger tastes bad, I=E2=80=99m gonna short the s=
tock,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s legitimate research. If =
you log into Instagram=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Chey this app is good=E2=80=9D =
and buy Meta stock, that=E2=80=99s good.=C2=A0People are <em>supposed</em> =
to go around observing companies=E2=80=99 products and services, evaluating=
 them, and incorporating those evaluations into their investment decisions.=
 That=E2=80=99s how stock prices become efficient and how capital gets allo=
cated to good uses rather than bad ones.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly if you=E2=80=99re on a plane and the=
 door blows off and you think =E2=80=9Cthis plane is poorly constructed, I=
=E2=80=99m gonna short some stocks here,=E2=80=9D seems fine. What duty do =
you have to keep it confidential? Maybe there=E2=80=99s some fine print in =
your ticket contract but I doubt it. There are probably edge cases. What if=
 you are flying for a work trip: Do you owe some obligation to your employe=
r not to use the information to trade for your own account? Still probably =
not a huge enforcement priority to come after you.</p>
