<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, here=E2=80=99s a paper f=
inding that when bankers in New York are visiting the Federal Reserve Bank =
of New York a lot, that is bad for the=C2=A0stock market:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We introduce taxi ridership betwee=
n the Federal Reserve (Fed) Bank of New York and large financial institutio=
ns headquartered in New York City as a novel proxy for Fed=E2=80=93bank fac=
e-to-face interactions. We document a negative relation between past Fed=E2=
=80=93bank interactions and future stock market returns, particularly on da=
ys around the Fed=E2=80=99s public announcements. We also find significantl=
y elevated Fed=E2=80=93bank interactions immediately following the lifting =
of the Federal Open Market Committee blackout. Our findings suggest that th=
e Fed increases its information gathering via face-to-face interactions whe=
n it possesses negative private information about the condition of the econ=
omy.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The paper is =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33957045.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly9wdWJzb25saW5lLm=
luZm9ybXMub3JnL2RvaS9hYnMvMTAuMTI4Ny9tbnNjLjIwMjMuNDg4NQ/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB9bc77989" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">When Bankers Go to Hail: Insights into Fed=E2=80=
=93Bank Interactions from Taxi Data</a>,=E2=80=9D by Daniel Bradley, David =
Andrew Finer, Matthew Gustafson and Jared Williams, and I guess that makes =
sense: When the Fed is more worried about the economy, it meets with banker=
s more often, and measuring those meetings gives you some signal about the =
economy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that=C2=A0<em>taxi rides=C2=A0<=
/em>are a weaker measure of those meetings than they used to be.=C2=A0From =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33957045.258408/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTMxNDEyN=
DA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa2dc6a95" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the paper</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We generally employ a daily sample=
 that runs from January, 2009, through December, 2014, where each day is de=
fined as 5:00am through 4:59am the following day. The year 2014 saw a large=
 increase in the use of rideshare apps by businesses and the first public r=
elease of the taxi data under New York State=E2=80=99s Freedom of Informati=
on Law (Rao 2015, Saitto 2014, White 2015, Whong 2014). Significant pattern=
s in rides may reflect the movements of small sets of individuals, and subs=
titution by any of them away from taxis due to changes in business practice=
 or due to concerns about privacy could result in a significant loss of sig=
nal.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you wanted to measure bank/Fed meetings in =
2024, you=E2=80=99d use =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Uber data? (Or has everyone permanen=
tly gone virtual, and you=E2=80=99d use Zoom data?) I hope Uber Technologie=
s Inc. is selling that data to some hedge funds.</p>
